  })} />

  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What are the most important words to learn first in Scrabble?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "The 10 most important words to learn first are QI (11 pts), ZA (11 pts), OX (9 pts), XI (9 pts), XU (9 pts), JO (9 pts), AX (9 pts), EX (9 pts), KA (6 pts), and QAT (12 pts). These words let you play high-value tiles (Q, Z, X, J) without needing a U or long rack combinations, making them essential for beginners." }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Is QI a valid Scrabble word without using a U?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Yes! QI is valid in both SOWPODS and TWL dictionaries. It refers to the life force in Chinese philosophy (also spelled chi or ki). QI is the single most important word for beginners because it lets you play the Q tile (worth 10 points) without needing a U, which is extremely rare and valuable in competitive play." }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How many points can these 10 essential words score in Scrabble?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "The base scores range from 6 points (KA) to 12 points (QAT). However, placed on premium squares these words can score much more — QI on a Triple Letter Score becomes 31 points from just two tiles. Combined, mastering these 10 words gives you access to 93 base points of vocabulary that most beginners completely miss." }
      }
    ]
  })} />

  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 py-12">
    <article class="prose prose-invert prose-gray max-w-none">
      <nav class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-6 not-prose flex items-center gap-1">
        <a href="/blog/" class="hover:text-blue-400 transition-colors">← Blog</a>
        <span class="mx-1">›</span>
        <a href="/blog/beginner-guides/" class="hover:text-blue-400 transition-colors text-gray-300">Beginner Guides</a>
      </nav>

      <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-4">First 10 Words to Learn for Scrabble</h1>

      <div class="not-prose mb-8 flex items-center gap-3 text-sm text-gray-400">
        <time datetime="2026-06-15">June 15, 2026</time>
        <span class="w-1 h-1 rounded-full bg-gray-600"></span>
        <span>7 min read</span>
        <span class="w-1 h-1 rounded-full bg-gray-600"></span>
        <a href="/" class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 text-blue-400 hover:underline"><span aria-hidden="true">🔤</span> Word Finder</a>
      </div>

      <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-gray-300 mb-8">
        Every Scrabble champion started somewhere. Before you memorise obscure seven-letter bingos or master board control, there are exactly 10 words that will transform your game overnight. These short, high-scoring words let you play tiles that most beginners consider unusable — the Q without a U, the Z with nowhere to go, the X gathering dust on your rack. Learn these 10 words and you'll immediately start outscoring players who've been playing for years.
      </p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
        <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center justify-center gap-6 text-center">
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">10</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Words to Learn</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">93 pts</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Combined Base Score</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">2-3</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Letters Each</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">100%</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">SOWPODS Valid</p></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Why These 10 Words Matter</h2>

      <p>Scrabble gives you seven tiles at a time. Statistically, you'll draw high-value tiles like Q, Z, X, J, and K in roughly one out of every three racks. Most beginners panic when they see these tiles because the "obvious" words need supporting letters that might not be there. QU needs five more letters. JAZZ needs two Z tiles you'll never have simultaneously.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-blue-500/30 bg-blue-950/20">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-blue-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">💡 The Core Problem</p>
        <p class="text-base text-gray-200">High-value tiles are worth <span class="text-white font-medium">8-10 points each</span>, but they become a <span class="text-white font-medium">-10 penalty</span> if stuck on your rack at game end. These 10 words turn liabilities into assets — every single time.</p>
      </div>

      <p>These 10 words solve the problem completely. They're short (2-3 letters), so they fit anywhere on the board. They use exactly one high-value tile paired with one or two common tiles you'll almost always have. And they're all valid in SOWPODS (the international competitive dictionary), so they work in tournaments worldwide.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">The 10 Essential Words</h2>

      <p>Here they are, ranked by strategic importance. Every word is SOWPODS-valid and playable in competitive Scrabble.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 flex flex-wrap items-center justify-center gap-3">
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm"><span class="text-white font-bold">QI</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">11 pts</span></span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm"><span class="text-white font-bold">ZA</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">11 pts</span></span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm"><span class="text-white font-bold">OX</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">9 pts</span></span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm"><span class="text-white font-bold">XI</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">9 pts</span></span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm"><span class="text-white font-bold">XU</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">9 pts</span></span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm"><span class="text-white font-bold">JO</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">9 pts</span></span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm"><span class="text-white font-bold">AX</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">9 pts</span></span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm"><span class="text-white font-bold">EX</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">9 pts</span></span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm"><span class="text-white font-bold">KA</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">6 pts</span></span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm"><span class="text-white font-bold">QAT</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">12 pts</span></span>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">1. QI — The Most Important Word in Scrabble</h2>

      <div class="not-prose my-8 p-6 rounded-2xl border-2 border-amber-500/50 bg-gradient-to-r from-amber-950/30 to-yellow-950/20 relative overflow-hidden">
        <div class="absolute top-3 right-4 text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-widest text-amber-500/70">👑 #1 Essential</div>
        <p class="text-2xl font-black text-white tracking-wider mb-2">QI</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-amber-300 font-semibold mb-3">11 points • Q(10) + I(1) • No U required</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">The life force or vital energy in Chinese philosophy (also romanised as chi or ki). This single word transforms the Q tile from Scrabble's biggest liability into a reliable scoring play. On a Triple Letter Score, QI scores 31 points from just two tiles.</p>
      </div>

      <p>QI is universally considered the most important word in competitive Scrabble. The Q tile is worth 10 points but there's only one U in most racks. Without QI, you're often forced to exchange the Q — wasting an entire turn. With QI memorised, you can play the Q tile on almost any board state, as long as there's an I anywhere you can reach.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">2. ZA — The Z Tile's Best Friend</h2>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
          <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">✓ What It Means</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Short for pizza (South African slang). Valid in SOWPODS. An informal word adopted into the official Scrabble dictionary.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
          <p class="text-amber-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">⚡ Why It's Essential</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Z is worth 10 points. ZA only needs an A — the most common tile in the bag (9 copies). You'll almost always have one available.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>ZA scores 11 points base and fits into incredibly tight spaces. Because A is the most common vowel tile, you can reliably play ZA whenever you draw the Z. It also extends easily — ZAP, ZAG, ZAX are all valid follow-ups if you want to build on it later.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">3. OX — Simple, Powerful, Versatile</h2>

      <p>OX means a castrated bull — a word everyone knows but few think to play. At 9 points (O=1, X=8), it's one of the easiest high-scoring plays available. The real power of OX is its extensions: BOX, COX, FOX, GOX, HOX, LOX, NOX, POX, SOX, VOX, and OXO, OXEN, OXES, OXID. That's over a dozen words built from one two-letter foundation.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-blue-500/30 bg-blue-950/20">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-blue-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">💡 Extension Power</p>
        <p class="text-base text-gray-200">OX has <span class="text-white font-medium">12+ valid extensions</span> in SOWPODS. Learning OX gives you instant access to BOX, FOX, POX, SOX, VOX, LOX, and more — each scoring 9+ points before premium squares.</p>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">4. XI — The Greek Letter Play</h2>

      <p>XI is the 14th letter of the Greek alphabet (the one that looks like Ξ). It scores 9 points (X=8, I=1) and pairs the X tile with the second-most common letter in the bag. XI is particularly useful in parallel plays — laying it alongside an existing word to score in both directions simultaneously.</p>

      <p>Like QI, XI uses the extremely common I tile (there are 9 copies in a standard bag). This means whenever you have an X, you can almost certainly play either XI or one of the other X words on this list.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">5. XU — The Vietnamese Coin</h2>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-cyan-500/30 bg-cyan-950/10">
          <p class="text-cyan-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">📖 Definition</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">A monetary unit of Vietnam, equal to one hundredth of a dong. Valid in SOWPODS and TWL.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/10">
          <p class="text-purple-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">🎯 Strategic Value</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Gives you a third X-play option (alongside XI and AX). With XI, XU, AX, EX, and OX, you have FIVE two-letter X words — the X tile never gets stuck.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>XU scores 9 points and provides redundancy for your X plays. Between XI, XU, AX, EX, and OX you have five different two-letter options for the X tile. This means no matter what vowels or consonants surround your target square, you can almost always find a valid X placement.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">6. JO — Unlock the J Tile</h2>

      <p>JO is a Scottish word for sweetheart (think "bonnie lass" territory). The J tile is worth 8 points but has very few short-word options — JO is your primary outlet. At 9 points base (J=8, O=1), it turns a difficult tile into an easy score. JO also extends to JOB, JOE, JOG, JOT, JOW, JOY — all common words you already know.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
        <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center justify-center gap-6 text-center">
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">8 pts</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">J Tile Value</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">1 of 1</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">J Tiles in Bag</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">27 pts</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">JO on TLS</p></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">7. AX — The Chopping Play</h2>

      <p>AX is the American spelling of axe — a tool for chopping. Everyone knows this word, yet beginners rarely think to play it. At 9 points (A=1, X=8), AX combines the most common vowel with the third-highest-value consonant. It extends beautifully too: AXE, AXED, AXEL, AXES, AXLE. Each extension maintains the high X-value while building longer words.</p>

      <p>AX is particularly strong as a parallel play. Drop it next to an existing word so both the A and X form new words in the perpendicular direction, and you score the X tile in both directions.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">8. EX — The Prefix That Scores</h2>

      <p>EX means a former partner (as in "my ex") and is valid as a standalone two-letter word. At 9 points (E=1, X=8), it pairs the second-most common tile in the bag with X. The beauty of EX is that it's also a prefix — EXAM, EXIT, EXPO, EXUDE — making it a natural stepping stone to longer words as your vocabulary grows.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Tip:</span> EX works as both a standalone score and a bridge to longer words. Play EX now, then later extend it to EXAM or EXIT for even more points on your next turn.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Tip:</span> With E being the most common tile (12 copies in the bag), you will almost always have access to EX when you draw the X. It's your most reliable X-word backup.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">9. KA — The Egyptian Spirit</h2>

      <p>KA is the Egyptian word for the spirit or vital force believed to inhabit a body. The K tile is worth 5 points — less than Q, Z, X, or J — but it's still a premium tile that beginners struggle with. KA scores 6 points (K=5, A=1) and gives you a simple two-letter dump for K when nothing longer works.</p>

      <p>While 6 points seems modest compared to QI's 11, KA's real value is tempo. Instead of wasting a turn exchanging the K or forcing a low-scoring longer word, you play KA in a tight spot, score your 6 points, and draw a fresh tile that might unlock a bingo on your next turn.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">10. QAT — The Q Without U Powerhouse</h2>

      <div class="not-prose my-8 p-6 rounded-2xl border-2 border-amber-500/50 bg-gradient-to-r from-amber-950/30 to-yellow-950/20 relative overflow-hidden">
        <div class="absolute top-3 right-4 text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-widest text-amber-500/70">🌿 Bonus Word</div>
        <p class="text-2xl font-black text-white tracking-wider mb-2">QAT</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-amber-300 font-semibold mb-3">12 points • Q(10) + A(1) + T(1) • Still no U needed</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">An evergreen shrub (Catha edulis) whose leaves are chewed as a stimulant in East Africa and the Arabian Peninsula. QAT gives you a second Q-without-U option beyond QI, and at 12 points it's actually higher-scoring than its two-letter cousin.</p>
      </div>

      <p>QAT is your insurance policy. If the I tiles are all played or blocked, QAT gives you another escape route for the Q tile. It uses A and T — both extremely common tiles — so you'll rarely be stuck. Having both QI and QAT memorised means the Q tile is never a problem for you again.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Memorisation Strategy</h2>

      <p>Don't try to memorise all 10 at once. Group them by the tile they unlock:</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/10">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-purple-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">🧩 Learning Order</p>
        <div class="space-y-3">
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">1</span>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><strong class="text-white">Week 1 — Q words:</strong> QI and QAT. These solve your biggest problem tile immediately.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">2</span>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><strong class="text-white">Week 2 — X words:</strong> XI, XU, AX, EX, OX. Five words that make X your favourite tile.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">3</span>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><strong class="text-white">Week 3 — Z and J:</strong> ZA and JO. One word each — simple and effective.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">4</span>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><strong class="text-white">Week 4 — K word:</strong> KA. The final piece — now every premium tile has an outlet.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">How These Words Win Games</h2>

      <p>Knowing these 10 words creates a compound advantage that grows throughout every game you play:</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
          <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">⚡ No Wasted Turns</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">You never need to exchange tiles when Q, Z, X, J, or K appear. Every turn becomes a scoring opportunity instead of a recovery play.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
          <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">📈 Premium Square Access</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Two-letter words fit in tight spots near Triple Letter and Double Word squares that longer words can't reach. QI on a TLS = 31 points.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
          <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">🔄 Better Rack Flow</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Playing premium tiles immediately keeps your rack balanced. Dump the Z with ZA, draw a fresh tile, and increase your chances of building a 7-letter bingo.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
          <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">🛡️ No Endgame Penalties</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Unplayed tiles subtract from your final score. A stuck Q costs you 10 points (and gives your opponent 10). These words prevent that from ever happening.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Quick Reference Scores</h2>

      <div class="overflow-x-auto not-prose my-6">
        <table class="w-full text-sm border border-gray-700 rounded-lg overflow-hidden shadow-sm">
          <thead class="bg-gray-800">
            <tr>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-300">Word</th>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-300">Points</th>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-300">Meaning</th>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-300">On TLS</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody class="divide-y divide-gray-800">
            <tr class="bg-gray-900"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-bold">QI</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-amber-400">11</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">Life force (Chinese)</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-green-400">31</td></tr>
